<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-trig-intro" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Angles and Trigonometric Definitions</title>

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Be familiar with radian measure of angles, and standard notation related to angles. 
        </p>
      </li>      
      <li>
        <p>
          Use the right angled triangle definitions and the general definitions of the 6 trigonometric functions, and interchange between the two.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Be familiar with basic relationships between trigonometric functions.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Evaluate the 6 trigonometric functions without a calculator, for common angles such as those listed in <xref ref="trig-common" text="title"/>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>
   
  <assemblage><title>Where will this be used in calculus?</title>
    <p>
      Trigonometric functions are used extensively throughout calculus. Being able to work with, and evaluate, trigonometric functions is essential in many applications. Here are a few specific examples:
    </p>
    <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Trigonometric functions are used in many modeling contexts, for example when modeling wave motions. 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          A technique called trigonometric substitution allows us to solve integration problems such as <m>\int \sqrt{4-x^2} \ dx</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
        Optimization problems sometimes involve trigonometric relationships. For example, maximizing the area of a triangle given certain side lengths requires an understanding of trigonometric functions.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  </assemblage>

  <introduction>
    <p>    
      In this section, we will work with trigonometric functions. 
      We will see definitions of the six trigonometric functions both in terms of right angled triangles, and in terms of general angles. We will also examine relationships between the six functions.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection><title>Angle Notation</title>
   <p> 
    In calculus, we will mostly use radians to measure angles. This is because several formulas and techniques in calculus are much easier to work with when using radians (compared to degrees). If you are more familiar with angles measured in degrees, you may want to start by using this conversion chart. However, it is useful to develop a feel for radian measures (rather than converting to degrees each time).  
  </p>
  
 <assemblage><title>Radian angles</title>
    <p>
      Radians are a measure of the size of an angle. 
      In a circle, if you take the radius of the circle and lay that length along the circle's edge, the corresponding angle is <term> 1 radian<idx>radian</idx></term>. 
    </p>
    <!-- <p>
<url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#/media/File:Circle_radians.gif">Radians Illustration</url>
    </p> -->

  <image source="images/Circle_radians.gif" width="60%">
      <shortdescription>
          Radian angle measure.
        </shortdescription>
  </image>
  <p>Source
  <fn> 
    Source: https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Circle_radians.gif#/media/File:Circle_radians.gif
  </fn>
    </p>

    <p>
      The circumference <m>C</m> of a circle of radius <m>r</m> is <m>C=2\pi r</m>. This means that the angle corresponding to a full circle (360 degrees) is <m>2\pi</m> radians.
    </p>

    </assemblage>

<table><title>Correspondence between radian and degree measures in some common angles.</title>
  <tabular halign="center">
    <row header="yes" bottom="minor" >
      <cell>Degree </cell>      
      <cell>Radian </cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>0</cell>
      <cell>0</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>30^\circ</m></cell>
      <cell><m>\frac{\pi}{6}</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>45^\circ</m></cell>
      <cell><m>\frac{\pi}{4}</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>60^\circ</m></cell>
      <cell><m>\frac{\pi}{3}</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>90^\circ</m></cell>
      <cell><m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>120^\circ</m></cell>
      <cell><m>\frac{2\pi}{3}</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>135^\circ</m></cell>
      <cell><m>\frac{3\pi}{4}</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>150^\circ</m></cell>
      <cell><m>\frac{5\pi}{6}</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>180^\circ</m></cell>
      <cell><m>\pi</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>270^\circ</m></cell>
      <cell><m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>360^\circ</m></cell>
      <cell><m>2\pi</m></cell>
    </row>
  </tabular>

</table>

  <aside>
    <p>
      <alert> Study tip: </alert>
    </p>
    <p>  
      Use radians as much as possible and try to develop a feel for their size. For example, try to develop a feel for how large <m>\frac{\pi}{3}</m> radians is, withough needing to convert it to degrees. Use degrees as little as possible (or not at all) when you study calculus. If you use a calculator to check your answers, make sure it is set to radian mode. 
    </p>
  </aside>

  <p>
    An angle placed on the coordinate system is in <term>standard position <idx>Standard Position angle</idx></term> when its vertex is at the origin and its initial side is on the positive <m>x</m>-axis.  
    See <xref ref="fig-trig-intro1" />. A positive angle is measured in the counterclockwise direction. A negative angle is measured in the clockwise direction.
  </p>

<figure xml:id="fig-trig-intro1">
    <caption>Angle in standard position</caption>
  <title>Angle in standard position</title>
  <image source="images/trig1standard" width="60%">
      <shortdescription>
          Angle in standard position.
        </shortdescription>
  </image>
</figure>


  <p>
  The unit circle can be used to define trigonometric functions. <term>The unit circle</term> is a circle with centre at the origin, and radius 1, as shown in <xref ref="fig-trig-intro2"/>. 
  The point <m>P(x,y)</m> in <xref ref="fig-trig-intro2"/> is the <term>terminal point</term>. 
  The terminal point is defined as the point where the terminal side of an angle (in standard position) intersects the unit circle. The <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> values of the point <m>P(x,y)</m> will be important in the definitions of the trigonometric functions. 
  </p>

<figure xml:id="fig-trig-intro2">
    <caption>A point on the unit circle</caption>
  <title>A point on the unit circle</title>
  <image source="images/trig1unit" width="70%">
      <shortdescription>
          A point on the unit circle.
        </shortdescription>
  </image>
</figure>

    <assemblage><title>Greek letters</title><idx>Greek letters</idx>

    <p>
      We often (but not always) use Greek letters to represent angles. For example, <m>\theta</m> (theta), <m>\alpha</m> (alpha) and <m>\beta</m> (beta) are commonly used to represent angles. 
    </p>
      <p>
        For reference, here is a list of the names of some Greek letters commonly used in calculus, in case you are interested. 
      <md>
        <mrow> \alpha  &amp;- alpha</mrow>
        <mrow> \beta		&amp;- beta</mrow>
        <mrow> \gamma		&amp;- gamma \mbox{ (upper case } \Gamma) </mrow>
        <mrow> \delta		&amp;- delta \mbox{ (upper case } \Delta)</mrow>
        <mrow> \epsilon		&amp;- epsilon</mrow>
        <mrow> \theta		&amp;- theta</mrow>
        <mrow> \lambda		&amp;- lambda</mrow>
        <mrow> \mu		&amp;- mu</mrow>
        <mrow> \pi		&amp;- pi</mrow>
        <mrow> \sigma		&amp;- sigma \mbox{ (upper case } \Sigma)</mrow>
        <mrow> \tau		&amp;- tau</mrow>
        <mrow> \omega		&amp;- omega \mbox{ (upper case } \Omega)</mrow>
      </md>

      (This is not a full list of the Greek alphabet.)
    </p>
    </assemblage>

 <aside>
    <p>
      <alert> Study tip: </alert>
    </p>
    <p>  
      Repeat <xref ref="ex-angles"/> with many other angles, until you feel more amiliar with radian angles. For example, locate the following angles on the unit circle:
    <m>0, \frac{\pi}{6}, \frac{\pi}{4}, \frac{\pi}{3}, \frac{\pi}{2}, \frac{2\pi}{3}, \frac{3\pi}{4}, \frac{5\pi}{6}, \pi, \frac{7\pi}{6}, \frac{5\pi}{4}, \frac{4\pi}{3}, \frac{3\pi}{2}, \frac{5\pi}{3}, \frac{7\pi}{4}, \frac{11\pi}{6}, 2\pi</m>
   Also look at the negative equivalents of these angles. 
  </p>
  </aside>

<example xml:id="ex-angles"><title>Radians on unit circle</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Draw the following angles (given in radians) on the unit circle. 
       <me>\pi, \frac{\pi}{4}, \frac{7\pi}{4}, \frac{-\pi}{6}</me>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <image source="images/angle-pi" width="70%">  </image>
          <image source="images/angle-pi4" width="70%">  </image>
            <image source="images/angle-7pi4" width="70%">  </image>
              <image source="images/angle-pi6" width="70%">  </image>
      </p>
      </answer>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              The angle <m>\pi</m> corresponds to half of a full turn (180 degrees). 
            </p>
          </li>
           <li>
            <p>
              The angle <m>\frac{\pi}{4}</m> corresponds to a quarter of <m>\pi</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The angle <m>\frac{7\pi}{4}</m> brings us to Quadrant IV because it is only <m>\frac{\pi}{4}</m> smaller than a full turn. 
            </p>
          </li>
           <li>
            <p>
               The angle <m>\frac{-\pi}{6}</m> is in the clockwise direction, one 6th of <m>\pi</m> (and <m>\pi</m> corresponds to half of a full turn).
            </p>
          </li>                   
        </ul>
        <image source="images/angle-pi" width="70%">  </image>
          <image source="images/angle-pi4" width="70%">  </image>
            <image source="images/angle-7pi4" width="70%">  </image>
              <image source="images/angle-pi6" width="70%">  </image>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

<exercise xml:id="ex-trig-intro1"><title>Unit circle - FROM WEBWORK</title>
	<webwork source="Library/MC/Trigonometry/RadianTerminalPoint.pg" />
</exercise>
</subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="trig-def"><title>Definitions</title>
  <p>We will focus on six trigonometric functions: sine, cosine, tangent, cosecant, secant, and cotangent. It is important to be familiar with their definitions, both in terms of right angled triangles, and in terms of angles in standard position in a circle.   </p>
  
 <aside>
    <p>
      <alert> Study tip: </alert>
    </p>
    <p>  
      Some students like the neumonic SOH CAH TOA to help memorize these definitions. ``SOH'' refers to <m>\sin \theta = </m> Opposite / Hypothenuse, and similarly for CAH and TOA. 
    </p>
 </aside>

   <assemblage><title>Definitions of trigonometric functions - right angled triangles</title>
    <idx>Definitions of trigonometric functions - right angled triangles</idx>
    <p>
      Consider a right angled triangle, where one of the accute angles is <m>\theta </m>. This means <m>0 \lt \theta \lt \frac{\pi}{2}</m>. Then the trigonometric functions are defined as follows:
    </p>
    <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Sine: <m>\sin \theta = </m> Opposite / Hypothenuse
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Cosine: <m>\cos \theta = </m> Adjacent / Hypothenuse
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Tangent: <m>\tan \theta = </m> Opposite / Adjacent 
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  </assemblage> 
  
 <example><title>Evaluating basic trig</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      In the below right angled triangle, there is a right angle and two accute angles labelled <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m>. 
      The sides are 17, 15 and 8 units long, as indicated. 
      </p>
      <image source="images/trigintro1" width="50%">
      <shortdescription>
          A right angled triangle with sides 17, 15 and 8.
        </shortdescription>
  </image>
      <p>
      Evaluate the following trigonometric quanities. Answer with exact values. 
      </p>
      <ol>
      <li>
          <p>
            <m>
        \sin \alpha
      </m>
          </p>
        </li>
                <li>
          <p>
            <m>
        \sin \beta
      </m>
          </p>
        </li>
                <li>
          <p>
            <m>
        \tan \beta
      </m>
          </p>
        </li> 
                <li>
          <p>
            <m>
        \cos \alpha
      </m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <ol>
      <li>
          <p>
            <m>
        \sin \alpha = \frac{15}{17}
      </m>
          </p>
        </li>
                <li>
          <p>
            <m>
        \sin \beta = \frac{8}{17}
      </m>
          </p>
        </li>
                <li>
          <p>
            <m>
        \tan \beta = \frac{8}{15}
      </m>
          </p>
        </li> 
                <li>
          <p>
            <m>
        \cos \alpha = \frac{8}{17}
      </m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      </answer>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The hypthenuse of this triangle is 17. 
        The `opposite' of angle <m>\alpha</m> is 15, while the `opposite' of angle <m>\beta</m> is 8. The `adjacent' of angle <m>\alpha</m> is 8, while the `adjacent' of angle <m>\beta</m> is 15. Then use the definitions listed above. 
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

<exercise><title>Evaluating basic trig - HOMEMADE - NEW, PLEASE CHECK</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
      In the below right angled triangle, there is a right angle and two accute angles labelled <m>\gamma</m> and <m>\mu</m>. 
      The sides are 33, 56 and 65 units long, as indicated. 
      </p>
      <image source="images/trig9" width="50%">
      <shortdescription>
          A right angled triangle with sides 33, 56 and 65.
        </shortdescription>
  </image>
      <p>
      (Not randomizable) Evaluate the following trigonometric quanities. Answer with exact values. 
      </p>     
    </introduction>
  <webwork>
    <pg-code>
      Context("Fraction");

      $a = random(2,9,1);
      $ans1 = Compute("33/65")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );
      $ans2 = Compute("56/65")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );
      $ans3 = Compute("33/65")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );
      $ans4 = Compute("56/33")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );
      $ans5 = Compute("56/65")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );
      $ans6 = Compute("33/56")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );
      $ans7 = Compute("1089/4225")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );

         Context()->functions->disable('All');
         Context()->functions->enable('sqrt');
    </pg-code>

    <statement>
      <p>Use the triangle in the image and evaluate the following trigonometric quanities. Answer with exact values. </p>
      <p> (a) <m> \sin \gamma =</m>  <var name="$ans1" width="6"/>.</p>
      <p> (b) <m> \cos \gamma =</m>  <var name="$ans2" width="6"/>.</p>
      <p> (c) <m> \cos \mu =</m>  <var name="$ans3" width="6"/>.</p>
      <p> (d) <m> \tan \mu =</m>  <var name="$ans4" width="6"/>.</p>
      <p> (e) <m> \sin \mu =</m>  <var name="$ans5" width="6"/>.</p>
      <p> (f) <m> \tan \gamma =</m>  <var name="$ans6" width="6"/>.</p>
      <p> (g) <m> \left(\tan \gamma \right) \left(\cos \mu \right) \left(\sin \mu \right) =</m>  <var name="$ans7" width="6"/>.</p>
    </statement>
  </webwork>
  </exercise>

 <aside>
    <p>
      <alert> Study tip: </alert>
    </p>
    <p>  
      You should memorize all defitions of trigonometric functions, if you don't know them already. It is important to know both the definitions in terms of right angled triangles AND the definitions in terms of the circle.
    </p>
  </aside>

<assemblage><title>Definitions of trigonometric functions - general definition</title>
  <idx>Definitions of trigonometric functions - general definition</idx>
    <p>
      Let <m> \theta </m> be any angle in standard position in a circle centered at <m>(0,0)</m>. With <m>x, y</m> and <m>r</m> as in <xref ref="fig-trig-intro2"/>, we make the following definitions: 
    </p>
    <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\sin \theta = \frac{y}{r}</m> 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\cos \theta = \frac{x}{r}</m> 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\tan \theta = \frac{y}{x}</m> 
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  </assemblage> 

  <assemblage><title>Basic Trigonometric Identities</title>
    <p>
      The following relationships are all important.
    </p>
    <p>
    <ul>
        <li>
        <p>
          <m>\tan \theta = \frac{\sin \theta}{\cos \theta}</m> 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\csc \theta = \frac{1}{\sin \theta}</m> 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\sec \theta = \frac{1}{\cos \theta}</m> 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\cot \theta = \frac{1}{\tan \theta} = \frac{\cos \theta}{\sin \theta}</m> 
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  </assemblage> 

   <aside>
    <p>
      <alert> Study tip: </alert>
    </p>
    <p>  
      You should take the time to memorize all of the listed relationships between trigonometric functions, if you don't know them already. 
    </p>
  </aside>


  <!-- <exercise xml:id="trig-intro-CP1"><title>Definitions of <m>\sec \theta</m>, <m>\csc \theta</m> and <m>\cot \theta</m> - HOMEMADE</title>
  	<p>  
      Use the listed relationships between trigonomtric functions to find the definitions of secant, cosecant and cotangent. Write down lists of definitions first in terms of right angled triangles, then in terms of <m>x, y, r</m> in a circle.  
    </p>
    <hint>
    <p>
      We know that <m>\csc \theta = \frac{1}{\sin \theta}</m>. Therefore, in terms of right angled triangles, <m>\csc \theta = \frac{1}{opp/hyp} = \frac{hyp}{opp}</m>. Now do the same for secant and cotangent. 
      </p>  
      <p>  
      In terms of <m>x, y, r</m>, we see that <m>\csc \theta = \frac{1}{\sin \theta} = \frac{1}{y/r} = \frac{r}{y}</m>. Now do the same for secant and cotangent. 
    </p>
  </hint>
    <answer>
    <p>
      Does this work? </p>
  </answer>
  </exercise> -->
  

<exercise><title>Definitions of <m>\sec \theta</m>, <m>\csc \theta</m> and <m>\cot \theta</m> - HOMEMADE - NEW, PLEASE CHECK</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
       Use the above basic trigonimtric identities and definitions to find the definitions of secant, cosecant and cotangent. Do this first in terms of right angled triangles, then in terms of <m>x, y, r</m> in a circle. 
      </p>      
    </introduction>
    <webwork>
      <pg-code>
        Context("Numeric");
        $popup1 = PopUp(['?','opposite','adjacent','hypothenuse'],3);
        $popup2 = PopUp(['?','opposite','adjacent','hypothenuse'],1);
        $popup3 = PopUp(['?','opposite','adjacent','hypothenuse'],3);
        $popup4 = PopUp(['?','opposite','adjacent','hypothenuse'],2);
        $popup5 = PopUp(['?','opposite','adjacent','hypothenuse'],2);
        $popup6 = PopUp(['?','opposite','adjacent','hypothenuse'],1);
        $popup7 = PopUp(['?','x','y','r'],3);
        $popup8 = PopUp(['?','x','y','r'],2);
        $popup9 = PopUp(['?','x','y','r'],3);
        $popup10 = PopUp(['?','x','y','r'],1);  
        $popup11 = PopUp(['?','x','y','r'],1);
        $popup12 = PopUp(['?','x','y','r'],2);     
       </pg-code>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                We know that <m>\csc \theta = \frac{1}{\sin \theta}</m>. Therefore, in terms of right angled triangles, <m>\csc \theta = \frac{1}{opp/hyp} = </m> <var name="$popup1" form="popup"/> / <var name="$popup2" form="popup"/>. 
              </p>   
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                In right angled triangles, <m>\sec \theta =</m> <var name="$popup3" form="popup"/> / <var name="$popup4" form="popup"/>. 
              </p>   
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                In right angled triangles, <m>\cot \theta =</m> <var name="$popup5" form="popup"/> / <var name="$popup6" form="popup"/>. 
              </p>   
            </li>
            <li>
            <p>
              In terms of <m>x, y, r</m> on a circle, we see that <m>\csc \theta = \frac{1}{\sin \theta} = \frac{1}{y/r} = </m> <var name="$popup7" form="popup"/> / <var name="$popup8" form="popup"/>. 
            </p>   
            </li>   
            <li>
            <p>
              In terms of <m>x, y, r</m> on a circle,  <m>\sec \theta = </m> <var name="$popup9" form="popup"/> / <var name="$popup10" form="popup"/>. 
            </p>   
            </li>          
            <li>
            <p>
              In terms of <m>x, y, r</m> on a circle, we see that <m>\cot \theta = </m> <var name="$popup11" form="popup"/> / <var name="$popup12" form="popup"/>. 
            </p>   
            </li>  
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </webwork>
  </exercise>
</subsection>



